abstract: NEW-BRUNSWICK, N.J., Aug. 19.--Early last evening Hermann Stube, a German, entered the boarding house of Charles Kroses at Sayreville, and after ransacking the upper story and securing watches, jewelry, and other valuables, started off with his booty. Down stairs he met Mary McLaughlin, a servant, and, seizing her, demanded her money or her life. She screamed, and, with an oath, he drew and fired a revolver.

abstract: LITTLE ROCK, Ark., Aug. 20.--A singularly fatal accident occurred near Aurora, Madison County, Saturday. Samuel Williams, with his wife and 6-year-old child, was returning home from a field near the house when a large oak tree suddenly fell upon them. Williams's neck was broken and his skull crushed. The child was mashed into jelly, the mother escaping with serious injuries. Williams was an exConfederate soldier, having served three years in an Arkansas regiment.
